ual character," sexual patterns and attitudes that were understood to be uniquely American and to reflect contemporary transformations in politics, social life, gender roles, and culture. She considers how apparent shifts in sexual behavior shaped the nation's workplaces, homes, and families, and how these might be linked to racial and class differences.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aGender identityzUnited States. 0aKinsey, Alfred C. 0aSex - United States. 0aSexzUnited States. 0aSocial sciences. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh  aabnormal sexuality.  aalfred kinsey.  aclass.  acold war.  acultural studies.  adeviant sexuality.  aemasculation.  afemale sexuality.  afemininity.  afeminist theory.  agender roles.  agender studies.  agender.  ahistory.  ahomosexuality.  akinsey report.  amarital sexuality.  amarriage.  amasculinity crisis.  amasculinity.  anational identity.  anonfiction.  apolitics.  apost war america.  apostwar marriage.  aqueer theory.  arace.  asex.  asexual behavior.  asexual norms.  asexual practices.  asexuality.  asoldiers.  aveterans.  awomens rights.  awomens studies.  aworking women.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093004940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520930049423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520930049/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles